 .TH "X" "1" "July 2014" "x" "User Commands"
.SH
NAME
x \- handle list of directories
.SH
SYNOPSIS
x [\-aplrdci] [args]
AVAILABILITY
bash
.SH
DESCRIPTION
Stores directories in a handsome list.
.SH
OPTIONS
.TP
\fB\-a [folder]\fR
append folder to list. (default: current folder)
.TP
\fB\-p [folder]\fR
prepend folder to list. (default: current folder)
.TP
\fB\-l\fR
list folders.
.TP
\fB\-r [index]\fR
restore nth folder from list.
.TP
\fB\-d [index]\fR
delete nth folder from list.
.TP
\fB\-h\fR
show a brief help message
.SH
NOTES
.SS
Installation:
.P
Put something like this in your \fB$HOME/.bashrc\fR:
.RS
.P
\fB. /path/to/x.sh\fR
.P
Examples:
.P
# store current folder
:/$ x -a
.P
# store another folder
:/$ x -a /bin
.P
# list all stored folders
:/$ x -l
1   /
2   /bin
.P
# restore second entry "/bin"
:/$ x -r 2
:/bin$ sudo ./make_me_a_sandwich"
.SH
FILES
Data is stored in \fB$HOME/.x\fR. This can be overridden by setting the
\fB$_X_DATA\fR environment variable. When initialized, \fBz\fR will raise an
error if this path is a directory, and not function correctly.
.P
A man page (\fBx.1\fR) is provided.
.SH
